snippet.textDisplay: I'm not a fan of Apple but on this issue I have to side with them. It is the very nature of encryption that it isn't easily, or pragmatically, reversible without the decryption key. One of these guys says, "We don't want to weaken encryption..". Let's be clear, what he just said here is  "We DO want to weaken encryption!" If you create a backdoor someone will leak it or reverse engineer it. It'll be on the internet in 5 minutes!! Encryption will become meaningless. The purpose is to prevent Government or Apple themselves from data snooping which is precisely why Apple do this to reassure their customers about the data concentration they entrust Apple with. It is this simple: Either everyone has privacy and data security or nobody does. Unfortunately this sometimes protects bad actors but had they not had data protection then they might have chosen an alternate method. If you get access to Apple devices then they will use something else that is secure next time. Then Government will want access to those, and the terrorists will use something else next time, so we play this game of cat and mouse, all the while everybody else looses their privacy. The Government sees an Apple device as a concentration of information by bad actors and see them as desirable to access, which is true, but forget that had these devices not offered such protections then the terrorists would not have concentrated so much information on them and thus would no longer be so desirable to the Government. It is a fools game to consider trying to blame Apple or require them to weaken encryption by creating a backdoor.

The purpose is to prevent Government or Apple themselves from data snooping which is precisely why Apple do this to reassure their customers about the data concentration they entrust Apple with. It is this simple: Either everyone has privacy and data security or nobody does. Unfortunately this sometimes protects bad actors but had they not had data protection then they might have chosen an alternate method. If you get access to Apple devices then they will use something else that is secure next time. Then Government will want access to those, and the terrorists will use something else next time, so we play this game of cat and mouse, all the while everybody else looses their privacy. The Government sees an Apple device as a concentration of information by bad actors and see them as desirable to access, which is true, but forget that had these devices not offered such protections then the terrorists would not have concentrated so much information on them and thus would no longer be so desirable to the Government. It is a fools game to consider trying to blame Apple or require them to weaken encryption by creating a backdoor.

snippet.textDisplay:
To the apparently ignorant folks here (Jerri Crotft, Doug Lang, Larry Be, etc.) who believe the government and corporations are somehow lying to you about the efficacy of encryption: Please educate yourselves, because you sound really foolish. Mathematics doesn't lie. Secure storage and communications done correctly is extremely secure, and some methods of encryption are presently not reversible or crackable, even by the "magical" NSA. I suggest one or more of the books by Bruce Schneier, aimed at a general audience: "Secrets and Lies", "Schneier On Security" (also the name of his web site), "Liars and Outliers", or "Carry On." You'll thank me later...

As far as this farcical pleading by law enforcement to provide access to a "back door" or "master key" to the encryption of devices: The horse is out of the barn... the technology exists, and you can't prevent bad actors from using encryption. Encryption methods can be nested, one inside the other, so even if a device or system has a key accessible to law enforcement, it is very simple to have another encryption system at a higher level to which the law doesn't have access. All you end up with is another system of haves and have nots. The average Joe is denied access to security that bad actors that can avoid via extra effort and expense. You can't outlaw or prevent encryption. It saddens me that the A.G. either doesn't understand this or is attempting to conceal this from the press and public.

Since you can't prevent encryption, you shouldn't regulate it away from law-abiding citizens.
